1
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:05,000
https://slama.dev/comeback/

2
00:00:01,100 --> 00:00:01,920
Hi.

3
00:00:02,640 --> 00:00:04,900
I got everything except the mouthwash.

4
00:00:05,160 --> 00:00:07,360
I still have some, and Ozzak gargles with the green one anyway.

5
00:00:08,910 --> 00:00:11,790
I see you're in a good mood, bro.

6
00:00:12,430 --> 00:00:14,110
I'm doing great too.

7
00:00:14,650 --> 00:00:19,250
You won't believe it, some lady in the drugstore was just singing "Like Rain."

8
00:00:20,350 --> 00:00:22,050
People still remember me.

9
00:00:22,660 --> 00:00:23,940
At least once a month.

10
00:00:23,940 --> 00:00:28,050
Back in the day, whole women's dormitories used to sing my songs.

11
00:00:30,450 --> 00:00:32,550
You're still laughing at that.

12
00:00:32,650 --> 00:00:33,450
Uncle.

13
00:00:35,450 --> 00:00:39,450
We have to tell you something, but brace yourself for the worst.

14
00:00:40,950 --> 00:00:42,950
Ozzak found an air rifle.

15
00:00:43,260 --> 00:00:44,420
We have an air rifle?

16
00:00:44,720 --> 00:00:45,200
We don't.

17
00:00:45,220 --> 00:00:46,400
And we never did.

18
00:00:46,480 --> 00:00:46,980
We sure did.

19
00:00:47,240 --> 00:00:48,900
Look, uncle, let's not deal with that now.

20
00:00:48,900 --> 00:00:52,650
You watch TV and I'll tell Dad, okay?

21
00:00:54,650 --> 00:00:58,050
They're playing your song on TV right now.

22
00:00:58,060 --> 00:00:58,540
A lot.

23
00:00:58,540 --> 00:00:59,950
Hold on, it's about to come on.

24
00:01:00,290 --> 00:01:02,330
That's fantastic.

25
00:01:02,510 --> 00:01:04,050
I'm counting, about ten, nine.

26
00:01:04,290 --> 00:01:04,770
It's not.

27
00:01:04,810 --> 00:01:05,050
Eight.

28
00:01:05,350 --> 00:01:08,170
It's not, you're wrong that they're playing me on TV again.

29
00:01:08,170 --> 00:01:08,810
You'll see.

30
00:01:08,810 --> 00:01:10,350
Three, two, one, now.

31
00:01:17,250 --> 00:01:21,450
That's kind of weird, isn't it?

32
00:01:23,150 --> 00:01:30,460
Well, that was entertaining.

33
00:01:30,460 --> 00:01:33,160
And now, where's that air rifle?

34
00:01:33,540 --> 00:02:04,650
In the pantry.

35
00:02:05,050 --> 00:02:12,280
Four, two on the tram, plus the driver when she announced the route change, and in the drugstore almost all of them.

36
00:02:12,280 --> 00:02:13,160
That gives us.

37
00:02:13,940 --> 00:02:15,740
Eighty-two, but they're all women.

38
00:02:16,040 --> 00:02:18,240
Ozzak, your brother is a star again.

39
00:02:18,320 --> 00:02:19,640
Everyone's singing his songs.

40
00:02:21,140 --> 00:02:21,740
All women.

41
00:02:22,750 --> 00:02:23,690
So what?

42
00:02:23,790 --> 00:02:25,330
Only women are singing his songs.

43
00:02:25,410 --> 00:02:27,530
Well, he was always more of a ladies' singer.

44
00:02:27,750 --> 00:02:30,810
Mambo, have you seen the air rifle anywhere?

45
00:02:31,070 --> 00:02:31,950
It's not here.

46
00:02:33,250 --> 00:02:34,150
And anyway.

47
00:02:34,360 --> 00:02:35,400
What are you doing here?

48
00:02:35,400 --> 00:02:36,320
Tomas was supposed to be here.

49
00:02:36,580 --> 00:02:37,540
He's not coming.

50
00:02:38,160 --> 00:02:39,680
He's having a bit of a crisis.

51
00:02:41,600 --> 00:02:43,300
This will cheer him up.

52
00:02:48,450 --> 00:02:49,170
Hi, Ivuska.

53
00:02:49,450 --> 00:02:50,950
Put Dad on the phone, please.

54
00:02:51,460 --> 00:02:52,880
Just take it to him.

55
00:02:53,760 --> 00:02:54,500
Hello.

56
00:02:56,050 --> 00:02:57,150
I'm just taking a look.

57
00:02:58,750 --> 00:03:01,990
Tomas, I have something important for you.

58
00:03:02,250 --> 00:03:04,850
Get dressed quickly and come out here.

59
00:03:08,150 --> 00:03:09,250
Like Rain.

60
00:03:12,950 --> 00:03:17,450
I was going to look in the storage room, but I'll wait for this.

61
00:03:19,740 --> 00:03:21,480
Leos Mares singing Verdi.

62
00:03:21,700 --> 00:03:23,060
Do you like romance?

63
00:03:23,300 --> 00:03:23,500
Well.

64
00:03:24,050 --> 00:03:26,940
You know, I'm going through a phase right now.

65
00:03:28,450 --> 00:03:30,650
Oh please, you wouldn't happen to have it.

66
00:03:30,810 --> 00:03:33,050
"You'll Soak Into Me Like Rain."

67
00:03:34,150 --> 00:03:36,470
Unfortunately, that hasn't been released in years.

68
00:03:36,790 --> 00:03:38,510
But you're in great luck.

69
00:03:38,570 --> 00:03:40,470
The owner of this shop sings it.

70
00:03:40,510 --> 00:03:40,670
No.

71
00:03:41,350 --> 00:03:43,850
If you wait a moment, he'll come.

72
00:03:44,290 --> 00:03:45,150
That's him.

73
00:03:45,950 --> 00:03:46,550
So, what did you want?

74
00:03:47,670 --> 00:03:48,390
Hello.

75
00:03:48,850 --> 00:03:51,070
I wanted to thank you so very much.

76
00:03:51,650 --> 00:03:54,650
You know, life is somehow easier with you.

77
00:03:54,790 --> 00:03:55,310
What?

78
00:03:56,250 --> 00:03:59,250
You'll always be with me whenever I have my days.

79
00:03:59,350 --> 00:04:20,910
Is the boss here?

80
00:04:20,910 --> 00:04:21,650
Where else would he be?

81
00:04:21,790 --> 00:04:23,130
He doesn't even leave his room anymore.

82
00:04:23,550 --> 00:04:24,070
Good God.

83
00:04:30,150 --> 00:04:32,350
There's no point, he talks quietly.

84
00:04:34,850 --> 00:04:36,950
He really doesn't leave his room at all?

85
00:04:37,220 --> 00:04:37,740
Nope.

86
00:04:38,420 --> 00:04:41,320
I stuck a hair in the door to check if he opened it.

87
00:04:41,360 --> 00:04:42,820
And I put beef in gravy on the threshold.

88
00:04:42,860 --> 00:04:44,300
And in the morning neither was there.

89
00:04:45,590 --> 00:04:47,330
Turned out Ozzak ate both.

90
00:04:48,110 --> 00:04:48,670
Brutal!

91
00:04:49,190 --> 00:04:49,930
You'll get used to it.

92
00:04:50,450 --> 00:04:52,010
We can't just leave it like that.

93
00:04:52,350 --> 00:04:53,850
He's eaten worse things.

94
00:04:57,050 --> 00:05:01,150
Ivuska, your dad is clearly having a midlife crisis.

95
00:05:01,650 --> 00:05:03,650
He's having a crisis, I have a vacuum.

96
00:05:04,450 --> 00:05:05,550
We all have our problems.

97
00:05:05,650 --> 00:05:06,850
Don't underestimate it.

98
00:05:07,150 --> 00:05:09,210
Zoran got hit with it fifteen years ago.

99
00:05:09,250 --> 00:05:12,650
And if it weren't for the war in the Balkans, he never would've gotten over it.

100
00:05:14,650 --> 00:05:16,020
And what am I supposed to do about it?

101
00:05:16,350 --> 00:05:17,620
He has to sort it out himself?

102
00:05:17,950 --> 00:05:21,060
I don't even blame him that everyone at school makes fun of me.

103
00:05:21,250 --> 00:05:21,850
Iva, a man can't handle a midlife crisis alone.

104
00:05:24,160 --> 00:05:26,140
He needs to know that someone still cares about him.

105
00:05:27,050 --> 00:05:30,350
Yeah, if he started ironing, she'd see how much I'd care about him.

106
00:05:30,850 --> 00:05:33,050
Ivuska, where's our iron?

107
00:05:38,470 --> 00:05:38,870
Higher.

108
00:05:40,090 --> 00:05:40,490
Higher.

109
00:05:41,650 --> 00:05:42,050
Higher.

110
00:05:44,850 --> 00:05:45,250
Hi.

111
00:05:45,370 --> 00:05:45,670
Hi.

112
00:05:46,740 --> 00:05:47,200
Sis!

113
00:05:47,500 --> 00:05:48,420
We have a visitor.

114
00:05:49,050 --> 00:05:49,450
Hey, do you have any laundry that needs ironing?

115
00:05:51,330 --> 00:05:52,590
Everything's already ironed.

116
00:05:52,670 --> 00:05:54,370
Well, he can do it a second time, doesn't matter.

117
00:05:54,470 --> 00:05:56,090
Everything's already ironed twice.

118
00:05:57,650 --> 00:06:01,550
Sasa, do it at least for my sake, he's unbearable.

119
00:06:04,150 --> 00:06:06,350
It's still weird to keep laundry in the fridge though.

120
00:06:06,650 --> 00:06:08,750
I like being able to see into it.

121
00:06:11,650 --> 00:06:13,390
At night you can browse magazines in the light.

122
00:06:13,550 --> 00:06:16,050
Lexa, turn it off, everything's going to be cold.

123
00:06:18,690 --> 00:06:19,450
Well, I'm going.

124
00:06:20,050 --> 00:06:22,620
When I'm gone longer than fifteen minutes, he starts crying.

125
00:06:22,620 --> 00:06:22,960
Bye.

126
00:06:23,000 --> 00:06:23,420
Bye.

127
00:06:26,850 --> 00:06:29,850
The boys call them panties, but I don't mind.

128
00:06:30,340 --> 00:06:30,940
Ryan.

129
00:06:34,350 --> 00:06:34,950
Lower.

130
00:06:35,610 --> 00:06:36,210
Lower?

131
00:06:37,480 --> 00:06:38,080
Sis.

132
00:06:38,950 --> 00:06:48,550
Felix, he was the only one who believed in me.

133
00:06:51,110 --> 00:06:51,790
Hello.

134
00:06:52,250 --> 00:06:53,630
Oh, it's nice that you're here.

135
00:06:53,950 --> 00:06:55,350
Felix Varovsky.

136
00:06:55,950 --> 00:06:59,950
In '87 he beat Frantisek Janicek in the pocket knife of the year category.

137
00:07:01,050 --> 00:07:02,470
Ham and pasta is in the fridge.

138
00:07:05,150 --> 00:07:07,650
He won a golden mace and a Moskvitch.

139
00:07:08,450 --> 00:07:10,150
He always calls me "kid."

140
00:07:10,250 --> 00:07:11,460
I'm betting on you.

141
00:07:11,650 --> 00:07:13,220
And he wasn't the only one, Tomas.

142
00:07:13,850 --> 00:07:15,740
Michal Penk wanted that song back then.

143
00:07:16,150 --> 00:07:17,000
But Felix said no.

144
00:07:17,450 --> 00:07:19,300
This kid here will make it big.

145
00:07:19,650 --> 00:07:20,250
Meaning me.

146
00:07:20,750 --> 00:07:21,950
Felix died.

147
00:07:24,150 --> 00:07:26,450
But you're alive, Tomas, so do something.

148
00:07:26,950 --> 00:07:27,650
I'm ironing.

149
00:07:29,350 --> 00:07:33,350
If the commercial bothers you so much, try suing them to take it down.

150
00:07:33,550 --> 00:07:35,750
You didn't even get any money for it.

151
00:07:36,250 --> 00:07:38,350
Can't, I signed a contract with Felix.

152
00:07:38,350 --> 00:07:38,690
Well!

153
00:07:39,550 --> 00:07:40,210
A contract.

154
00:07:40,550 --> 00:07:41,410
With Felix.

155
00:07:41,410 --> 00:07:42,030
Yeah.

156
00:07:43,450 --> 00:07:46,050
When he showed up at Holeckova's, he wrote me a song.

157
00:07:46,250 --> 00:07:47,450
Wait, how did it go.

158
00:07:47,850 --> 00:07:51,550
And so ends the merry tale of a singer with a bald...

159
00:07:51,850 --> 00:07:56,350
See, you still sing beautifully.

160
00:08:00,350 --> 00:08:02,050
Your clothes look kind of wrinkled.

161
00:08:03,250 --> 00:08:04,750
Show me, I'll iron them for you.

162
00:08:17,250 --> 00:08:20,450
I'm just happy I'm not pregnant again, that's all.

163
00:08:25,650 --> 00:08:26,750
This can't go on like this.

164
00:08:27,250 --> 00:08:28,150
I know the feeling.

165
00:08:29,550 --> 00:08:30,750
It was close to Christmas.

166
00:08:33,350 --> 00:08:35,450
Aren't there some disturbances brewing in the Balkans?

167
00:08:35,750 --> 00:08:37,850
Zoran said nothing major.

168
00:08:38,950 --> 00:08:41,750
And the nickname his uncle gave him doesn't exactly help either.

169
00:08:43,050 --> 00:08:44,150
"One-pad" and write it on a sanitary pad.

170
00:08:46,950 --> 00:08:48,130
That's what she calls him at home too.

171
00:08:48,130 --> 00:08:48,530
Yeah.

172
00:08:49,350 --> 00:08:51,550
And the more she laughs at him, the more Dad irons.

173
00:08:51,650 --> 00:08:54,410
Ivuska, your dad could really use a success.

174
00:08:54,410 --> 00:08:56,830
And what else does he want? They're already playing him on "The Perfect Woman."

175
00:08:57,330 --> 00:09:00,090
I think he needs to sing again.

176
00:09:00,250 --> 00:09:02,450
Well, that would really wipe the smirk off Ozzak's face.

177
00:09:02,550 --> 00:09:03,710
See, all positives.

178
00:09:05,040 --> 00:09:06,080
That sank in.

179
00:09:08,050 --> 00:09:09,050
Felix died, but I have his son's contact.

180
00:09:10,600 --> 00:09:11,900
Maybe he'd manage him.

181
00:09:12,450 --> 00:09:15,100
No, everyone's already making fun of me.

182
00:09:15,100 --> 00:09:16,600
You want him to start starching too?

183
00:09:24,340 --> 00:09:26,100
Hey, you didn't go to the Nazareth concert?

184
00:09:26,520 --> 00:09:27,860
They kicked me out at the entrance.

185
00:09:28,850 --> 00:09:31,250
They noticed the creases on my jeans.

186
00:09:32,850 --> 00:09:33,550
Can you see anything?

187
00:09:35,850 --> 00:09:37,550
I feel like he even ironed my hair.

188
00:09:38,950 --> 00:09:39,840
Where is he anyway?

189
00:09:39,840 --> 00:09:41,700
At Holeckova's, he's got some rags there.

190
00:09:41,920 --> 00:09:42,640
Great.

191
00:09:42,740 --> 00:09:43,880
I'm going to go get a bit rumpled.

192
00:09:44,450 --> 00:09:45,640
It's still your fault.

193
00:09:45,640 --> 00:09:46,000
Mine?

194
00:09:46,440 --> 00:09:46,920
Yeah, yours.

195
00:09:46,920 --> 00:09:49,250
You keep picking on him and he's falling apart.

196
00:09:50,250 --> 00:09:52,250
Well, true, he's a pretty easy target.

197
00:09:52,850 --> 00:09:54,090
Maybe I'll go back to picking on Mambo.

198
00:09:54,350 --> 00:09:55,450
At least she fights back.

199
00:09:57,350 --> 00:09:58,050
I won't.

200
00:09:58,850 --> 00:09:59,750
I enjoy it.

201
00:10:01,250 --> 00:10:02,890
Uncle, he's your brother though.

202
00:10:02,890 --> 00:10:03,490
And I'm his.

203
00:10:04,380 --> 00:10:05,720
You know how embarrassed I am because of him?

204
00:10:06,020 --> 00:10:07,260
You know what my friends call me?

205
00:10:07,500 --> 00:10:07,900
Ozzak.

206
00:10:08,080 --> 00:10:08,200
Yeah.

207
00:10:08,340 --> 00:10:08,600
And?

208
00:10:08,940 --> 00:10:11,380
They'd also show off if they found out who my brother is.

209
00:10:11,700 --> 00:10:13,340
Be nicer to him, at least for my sake.

210
00:10:13,750 --> 00:10:15,480
But it's not that simple.

211
00:10:15,480 --> 00:10:16,300
Every time I-

212
00:10:17,630 --> 00:10:18,550
I just can't help it.

213
00:10:18,950 --> 00:10:21,290
Imagine if he were sick, if he were dying.

214
00:10:21,470 --> 00:10:22,250
That would be intense.

215
00:10:22,410 --> 00:10:23,570
Would you also tell him what his situation is?

216
00:10:23,750 --> 00:10:24,310
If he asked?

217
00:10:24,810 --> 00:10:27,130
Wait, I'll die first anyway, I'm older.

218
00:10:27,770 --> 00:10:30,170
Uncle, you always have to tell him it's going to be fine.

219
00:10:30,790 --> 00:10:31,230
Really?

220
00:10:32,350 --> 00:10:35,250
It's simple, just say everything in reverse.

221
00:10:36,450 --> 00:10:38,820
Like, he's not embarrassing and he can sing?

222
00:10:40,050 --> 00:10:41,650
Yeah, it'll make him really happy.

223
00:10:43,050 --> 00:10:47,150
And if you keep it up until the concert, I'll tell you where he hides the air rifle.

224
00:10:48,030 --> 00:10:48,470
Iva?

225
00:10:50,250 --> 00:10:51,250
What concert?

226
00:11:00,050 --> 00:11:01,650
One of the four musketeers at six o'clock.

227
00:11:02,250 --> 00:11:02,950
Sandokan.

228
00:11:08,350 --> 00:11:09,510
He's ironing at the neighbor's.

229
00:11:09,950 --> 00:11:11,950
She's pretty, almost as pretty as you.

230
00:11:13,450 --> 00:11:16,450
I spoke with Artur and the situation isn't good.

231
00:11:16,850 --> 00:11:18,100
The concert won't happen.

232
00:11:18,100 --> 00:11:18,760
Too bad.

233
00:11:20,850 --> 00:11:27,620
It turned out Felix really did bet on Tomas, but he bet that he'd be so stage-frightened he wouldn't even get on stage.

234
00:11:27,620 --> 00:11:29,900
He even won once in Jelubevany.

235
00:11:31,530 --> 00:11:32,090
Poor guy.

236
00:11:32,090 --> 00:11:35,030
Uncle, you're only supposed to talk backwards to Dad.

237
00:11:35,030 --> 00:11:35,590
I'm practicing.

238
00:11:37,150 --> 00:11:39,540
We'll have to manage without Artur.

239
00:11:39,750 --> 00:11:42,040
It's great that you came up with this.

240
00:11:42,250 --> 00:11:44,000
I just don't know where it should be.

241
00:11:44,350 --> 00:11:45,250
How about Strahov?

242
00:11:46,350 --> 00:11:47,850
For God's sake, are you joking?

243
00:11:48,390 --> 00:11:49,470
I've been his fan my whole life.

244
00:11:50,270 --> 00:11:50,830
Really?

245
00:11:52,450 --> 00:11:53,650
Would I lie to you?

246
00:11:54,250 --> 00:11:56,150
You're not as dumb as you look either.

247
00:11:57,120 --> 00:11:57,680
Thank you.

248
00:11:58,550 --> 00:12:00,450
But Strahov right off the bat.

249
00:12:00,550 --> 00:12:03,690
How about somewhere outside Prague, so he's not under so much pressure?

250
00:12:03,690 --> 00:12:04,110
Sure.

251
00:12:04,450 --> 00:12:06,850
Find a town with the most women in the 40+ category.

252
00:12:07,450 --> 00:12:08,550
Excellent idea.

253
00:12:08,650 --> 00:12:09,610
Total nonsense.

254
00:12:09,610 --> 00:12:10,370
Thanks, uncle.

255
00:12:18,760 --> 00:12:19,240
Hi.

256
00:12:19,650 --> 00:12:20,250
Lida.

257
00:12:22,150 --> 00:12:25,150
She'll come as soon as she finishes ironing the curtain with the amateur theater group.

258
00:12:26,000 --> 00:12:26,480
The coat.

259
00:12:27,160 --> 00:12:30,500
But the jacket is missing buttons and the rear looks like it's been shot through or something.

260
00:12:30,700 --> 00:12:32,360
Maybe Pinkrat hid the air rifle in there.

261
00:12:33,300 --> 00:12:33,940
So?

262
00:12:34,280 --> 00:12:35,900
Did you find that 40+ town?

263
00:12:35,900 --> 00:12:36,600
I did.

264
00:12:36,800 --> 00:12:37,280
Babice.

265
00:12:37,660 --> 00:12:38,680
But nothing will come of it.

266
00:12:38,760 --> 00:12:40,380
They're booked solid through the end of the year.

267
00:12:40,600 --> 00:12:41,160
Listen.

268
00:12:41,580 --> 00:12:45,460
Hlozek, Kotvald, Jakub Smolik, Hlozek with Kotvald, and Sagvan Tofy.

269
00:12:45,760 --> 00:12:47,920
Tomas probably isn't the only one with depression.

270
00:12:48,420 --> 00:12:50,020
No, I won't have a beer.

271
00:12:51,350 --> 00:12:52,000
He'll have a beer.

272
00:12:52,450 --> 00:12:53,150
And slowly.

273
00:12:53,790 --> 00:12:54,350
Quickly.

274
00:12:56,050 --> 00:12:57,450
Make up your damn minds.

275
00:12:59,030 --> 00:13:01,470
I get oversensitive too when I have my period.

276
00:13:01,610 --> 00:13:04,370
I'd love to hear absolutely everything about that.

277
00:13:06,150 --> 00:13:08,850
Isn't Mr. Ozzak also in a bad mental state?

278
00:13:09,130 --> 00:13:11,090
He's the best he's been in the last ten years.

279
00:13:13,170 --> 00:13:13,690
Auntie.

280
00:13:13,930 --> 00:13:14,450
Yes?

281
00:13:15,950 --> 00:13:18,100
Could you do something for my dad?

282
00:13:18,100 --> 00:13:18,840
Depends on what.

283
00:13:20,650 --> 00:13:22,750
We'd need him to sing here.

284
00:13:23,250 --> 00:13:24,350
Absolutely not.

285
00:13:24,360 --> 00:13:24,880
Never.

286
00:13:25,350 --> 00:13:27,950
His songs are only good for driving Ozzak away.

287
00:13:30,750 --> 00:13:31,450
They're not.

288
00:13:32,400 --> 00:13:33,440
They're beautiful.

289
00:13:35,050 --> 00:13:37,650
It's like someone's telling me everything will be all right again.

290
00:13:38,350 --> 00:13:40,150
That I'll live a normal life again.

291
00:13:40,850 --> 00:13:42,550
That my kids will turn out okay.

292
00:13:43,250 --> 00:13:45,350
And that I finally won't be alone anymore.

293
00:13:45,820 --> 00:13:47,800
Good thing it only lasts a week, right?

294
00:13:49,440 --> 00:13:50,900
So it can be at the Badger?

295
00:13:51,850 --> 00:13:53,250
Absolutely not.

296
00:13:53,950 --> 00:13:56,630
Come on auntie, people, Ozzak would want it too, right uncle?

297
00:13:56,630 --> 00:13:57,190
Yeah.

298
00:13:57,530 --> 00:13:58,590
I'm not pouring you any more.

299
00:14:01,050 --> 00:14:01,730
Well this is really fun then.

300
00:14:01,850 --> 00:14:10,350
It'll work out.

301
00:14:11,450 --> 00:14:13,750
We have a week for this, right?

302
00:14:32,650 --> 00:14:36,250
He's not up for it, I'll call Berusek and cancel the big top.

303
00:14:36,550 --> 00:14:39,810
Dad, we have something better for you than ironing.

304
00:14:39,810 --> 00:14:40,330
Starching.

305
00:14:41,450 --> 00:14:42,250
Singing.

306
00:14:46,720 --> 00:14:47,220
Me?

307
00:14:48,250 --> 00:14:48,950
Singing?

308
00:14:49,550 --> 00:14:50,650
Like here?

309
00:14:51,050 --> 00:14:52,050
And live?

310
00:14:52,450 --> 00:14:54,470
You've always been best live.

311
00:14:54,470 --> 00:14:54,970
What?

312
00:14:54,970 --> 00:14:56,850
You always used to tell me to lip-sync.

313
00:14:57,150 --> 00:14:58,570
I didn't always tell you that.

314
00:14:58,570 --> 00:14:59,540
Yes you did.

315
00:14:59,900 --> 00:15:03,340
Wait, but I can't anymore and I don't have and...

316
00:15:03,340 --> 00:15:04,980
And why is it so soon?

317
00:15:05,160 --> 00:15:06,240
It has to be by Saturday.

318
00:15:06,740 --> 00:15:08,200
Simona will already have something then.

319
00:15:08,380 --> 00:15:09,580
More like she won't have something.

320
00:15:09,580 --> 00:15:12,350
And whose idea was it for me to sing?

321
00:15:12,990 --> 00:15:13,490
Well...

322
00:15:13,490 --> 00:15:13,970
Ozzak's.

323
00:15:14,450 --> 00:15:16,450
That would never in a million years occur to me.

324
00:15:17,050 --> 00:15:20,950
All right, Ivuska, I need to go rehearse.

325
00:15:28,350 --> 00:15:28,700
Fine.

326
00:15:29,250 --> 00:15:30,350
What if nobody comes?

327
00:15:31,050 --> 00:15:32,750
I have the papers for a bus.

328
00:15:34,650 --> 00:15:38,850
Tell me the ladies from Babice wouldn't love a trip to the capital.

329
00:15:40,150 --> 00:15:42,160
You're as dumb as you look.

330
00:15:42,850 --> 00:15:43,750
He meant well.

331
00:15:50,950 --> 00:15:58,580
You'll soak into me like rain and I'll soak into you, you won't find such happiness.

332
00:15:59,250 --> 00:16:09,640
Even if you went to heaven, when you carry me away like a hurricane, I won't care that I don't know where to land.

333
00:16:09,640 --> 00:16:12,240
You'll soak into me like rain.

334
00:16:14,550 --> 00:16:17,500
Oh, sorry bro, I, I was rehearsing.

335
00:16:17,500 --> 00:16:18,960
That helps.

336
00:16:18,960 --> 00:16:23,150
I don't know, I don't think it's a very good song.

337
00:16:23,650 --> 00:16:28,650
Felix claimed a person wrote it, but it was actually that computer from Slusovice.

338
00:16:28,650 --> 00:16:29,790
The one that wrote for Kamelie.

339
00:16:31,250 --> 00:16:32,750
I already knew that.

340
00:16:33,210 --> 00:16:33,650
Really?

341
00:16:33,650 --> 00:16:35,350
Felix said nobody knew.

342
00:16:35,850 --> 00:16:37,550
He even made up a pseudonym for it.

343
00:16:39,150 --> 00:16:42,440
But I wanted to sing my own songs, but Felix never let me.

344
00:16:42,440 --> 00:16:43,100
Don't know why.

345
00:16:43,460 --> 00:16:43,900
Weird.

346
00:16:44,860 --> 00:16:45,300
Right?

347
00:16:45,750 --> 00:16:46,900
But I think I've got what it takes.

348
00:16:47,150 --> 00:16:50,540
I'd write it differently though, you know, from the heart.

349
00:16:50,650 --> 00:16:51,820
Yes, sincerely, from the heart.

350
00:16:52,250 --> 00:16:55,450
You get it, so people can see who I really am, what kind of person I am.

351
00:16:55,770 --> 00:16:56,630
Where are you going?

352
00:16:57,950 --> 00:16:59,150
I feel sick.

353
00:16:59,550 --> 00:17:00,550
I'm not going to the pub.

354
00:17:04,050 --> 00:17:05,250
Yeah, my own song.

355
00:17:05,750 --> 00:17:07,050
My very own song.

356
00:17:16,050 --> 00:17:20,850
We're brothers, me and Ozzak.

357
00:17:22,150 --> 00:17:26,650
This is for you, a beer in the freezer.

358
00:17:28,750 --> 00:17:30,850
It's dumb having beer in the freezer.

359
00:17:31,330 --> 00:17:31,890
Tomas.

360
00:17:32,830 --> 00:17:33,390
Marcelka.

361
00:17:34,750 --> 00:17:35,560
What are you doing here?

362
00:17:35,560 --> 00:17:36,880
What were you singing?

363
00:17:37,980 --> 00:17:39,500
I'm writing my own song.

364
00:17:39,720 --> 00:17:41,660
But Radim Obvod always used to write for you.

365
00:17:41,860 --> 00:17:43,300
And where's he now?

366
00:17:43,950 --> 00:17:46,040
Probably off somewhere designing rockets.

367
00:17:47,150 --> 00:17:49,450
And this one will be different, more human.

368
00:17:50,250 --> 00:17:51,240
About my loved ones.

369
00:17:51,750 --> 00:17:53,100
That's lovely.

370
00:17:53,550 --> 00:17:55,520
About all of them?

371
00:17:55,750 --> 00:17:56,650
Every single one.

372
00:17:56,650 --> 00:18:00,800
Just tell me, what rhymes with "Ozzak"?

373
00:18:00,800 --> 00:18:01,160
Lout.

374
00:18:01,340 --> 00:18:02,340
That rhymes perfectly.

375
00:18:02,460 --> 00:18:03,700
Marcelka, I'm serious.

376
00:18:04,250 --> 00:18:05,930
And what about, like Pavel Vrba.

377
00:18:06,150 --> 00:18:07,250
Ozzak, Ozzak, Cossack.

378
00:18:09,450 --> 00:18:10,650
Ozzak, a horse wouldn't eat.

379
00:18:11,250 --> 00:18:14,840
Say Ozzak, Cossack, fry up.

380
00:18:14,840 --> 00:18:15,860
That's stupid.

381
00:18:16,280 --> 00:18:18,100
But no, because there would be a train station.

382
00:18:18,480 --> 00:18:19,520
What train station?

383
00:18:20,320 --> 00:18:22,160
I don't know, like a symbol of a journey.

384
00:18:22,160 --> 00:18:25,560
Ozzak isn't going anywhere right now, I'm the one going to Babice.

385
00:18:25,850 --> 00:18:27,950
Well, have a good trip, Marcelka.

386
00:18:32,050 --> 00:18:33,550
Marcelka, little bottom.

387
00:18:57,650 --> 00:18:58,750
Aren't you at swimming?

388
00:18:59,250 --> 00:19:00,850
I can't go to the pool this week, but I'm all the more excited to hear your dad sing again.

389
00:19:04,920 --> 00:19:06,580
I'll stay here and I won't sleep under a bridge.

390
00:19:06,840 --> 00:19:08,880
Uncle, Dad needs this.

391
00:19:09,980 --> 00:19:10,520
Where is he?

392
00:19:11,350 --> 00:19:12,150
In the bathroom.

393
00:19:12,350 --> 00:19:15,250
He locked himself in and said he won't sing.

394
00:19:15,550 --> 00:19:17,050
I don't feel like doing it live anyway.

395
00:19:19,350 --> 00:19:22,250
Marcela called, she's already looking for a place to park the bus.

396
00:19:28,850 --> 00:19:29,650
Is that the music?

397
00:19:29,810 --> 00:19:31,150
I'll be normal now.

398
00:19:33,490 --> 00:19:34,190
Oh well.

399
00:19:43,150 --> 00:19:44,860
You're the best, you can do this.

400
00:19:45,150 --> 00:19:46,350
Everyone will applaud.

401
00:19:47,050 --> 00:19:48,470
Ozzak, I'm not an idiot.

402
00:19:48,470 --> 00:19:48,870
You're not?

403
00:19:49,250 --> 00:19:50,750
You're saying everything backwards, aren't you?

404
00:19:50,870 --> 00:19:51,210
No.

405
00:19:52,750 --> 00:19:54,110
I thought so.

406
00:19:54,350 --> 00:19:56,750
Ivuska told me to practice for when you're dying.

407
00:19:58,050 --> 00:19:59,130
She's a good girl.

408
00:19:59,250 --> 00:19:59,810
She is.

409
00:20:00,050 --> 00:20:00,910
Isn't she?

410
00:20:00,910 --> 00:20:01,510
She is.

411
00:20:02,360 --> 00:20:03,700
And Marcela is a cow.

412
00:20:04,810 --> 00:20:06,530
There we go, you're finally talking normally.

413
00:20:06,630 --> 00:20:07,950
Don't talk about Marcelka like that!

414
00:20:07,970 --> 00:20:09,010
Do you know what she's doing for us?

415
00:20:09,150 --> 00:20:11,170
As soon as I say what I think, you chew me out!

416
00:20:12,350 --> 00:20:13,620
Are you saying I can't do it?

417
00:20:13,850 --> 00:20:14,650
How am I supposed to talk?

418
00:20:14,920 --> 00:20:15,280
You can't.

419
00:20:16,250 --> 00:20:16,950
You can.

420
00:20:24,750 --> 00:20:26,550
Tomorrow I'd be laughing at you.

421
00:20:27,290 --> 00:20:28,870
But today you're making me emotional!

422
00:20:30,930 --> 00:20:31,290
Simona!

423
00:20:34,550 --> 00:20:35,150
Don't screw this up now.

424
00:20:35,650 --> 00:20:36,750
Yes, I'll have a shot.

425
00:21:03,350 --> 00:21:06,950
Radim Obvod, lyrics, Rene Relem.

426
00:21:07,150 --> 00:21:12,120
But did you know that besides writing songs they also designed factories?

427
00:21:13,150 --> 00:21:16,220
Now I'm going to get personal.

428
00:21:16,750 --> 00:21:19,250
You know, I've been ironing a lot lately.

429
00:21:19,750 --> 00:21:23,950
And I realized that life isn't a standing lemonade.

430
00:21:24,750 --> 00:21:31,750
And in these moments what matters is whether your loved ones care about you and you care about them.

431
00:21:31,750 --> 00:21:33,210
I can't believe it.

432
00:21:33,210 --> 00:21:38,950
And I do care about my loved ones.

433
00:21:39,250 --> 00:21:43,550
That's why I wrote them a song.

434
00:23:21,810 --> 00:23:22,590
Those are pellets.

435
00:23:22,750 --> 00:23:23,730
I'll take the money then.

436
00:23:25,040 --> 00:23:26,540
Handbag, Cinderella, little bottom.

437
00:23:26,620 --> 00:23:28,500
What's so damn hard about that?

438
00:23:36,460 --> 00:23:37,160
I'll definitely come.

439
00:23:37,420 --> 00:23:37,780
Goodbye.

440
00:23:39,260 --> 00:23:42,720
So?

441
00:23:43,740 --> 00:23:44,100
Wonderful.

442
00:23:46,370 --> 00:23:46,730
Terrible.

443
00:23:47,500 --> 00:23:47,860
Thanks.

444
00:23:50,570 --> 00:23:51,470
How are you feeling, Dad?

445
00:23:51,830 --> 00:23:52,190
Wonderful.

446
00:23:52,850 --> 00:23:54,670
Awesome, everything back to normal?

447
00:23:54,670 --> 00:23:55,110
No, no.

448
00:23:56,050 --> 00:23:59,650
Marcelka is setting up more gigs for me.

449
00:24:00,070 --> 00:24:01,390
Mambo, keep an eye on me.

450
00:24:01,770 --> 00:24:02,930
I know where the air rifle is now.

451
00:24:08,850 --> 00:24:14,840
I stoke up at the station of longing, from the warmth of your embrace, I ride north, I'm no longer with you.

452
00:24:19,150 --> 00:24:25,650
It's a lonely and long road, only the disco ball points the way with its head.

453
00:24:26,150 --> 00:24:32,150
You ask where I am, I travel around playing gigs and I miss your laughter.

454
00:24:34,250 --> 00:24:49,450
I hope you'll believe that all these decibels mean nothing, I'd give everything I had just so you'd know.

455
00:24:51,650 --> 00:24:57,950
That it breeds anger for you.
